{{Orphan|date=August 2016}}

'''Josef Vincent Polišenský''' (1915–2001) was a Czech academic historian and Latin Americanist. He is best known in the English-speaking world for his book ''Tragic Triangle: The Netherlands, Spain and Bohemia, 1617–1621'' (Prague, Charles University, 1991), a study of the international political context of the [[Bohemian Revolt]].

His earlier study of the Bohemian Revolt, ''The Thirty Years War'', was translated into English by [[Robert John Weston Evans|R.J.W. Evans]] and published in England by B. T. Batsford (1970) and in the U.S. by University of California Press (1971).

He also wrote a general history of Bohemia, Moravia, Silesia, and Slovakia in a 1947 book, ''History of Czechoslovakia in Outline''.

==Sources==
*[[Robert John Weston Evans|R.J.W. Evans]], "A Czech Historian in Troubled Times: J.V. Polišenský", ''[[Past & Present (journal)|Past & Present]]'' 176 (2002), pp.&nbsp;257–274.

