{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}} {{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}} {{more footnotes|date=April 2015}} '''Radhakamal Mukerjee''' (1889–1968), a leading [[intellectual|thinker]] and [[social science|social scientist]] of modern [[India]], was Professor of [[Economics]] and [[Sociology]] and Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Lucknow]]. Mukerjee played an important and constructive role in the [[Indian independence movement]]. He was a highly original [[philosopher of history]] and a discerning interpreter of [[culture]] and [[civilization]] and a 1962 recipient of the third highest Indian civilian honour of the [[Padma Bhushan]].<ref name="Padma Awards">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2016 |accessdate=January 3, 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http%3A%2F%2Fmha.nic.in%2Fsites%2Fupload_files%2Fmha%2Ffiles%2FLST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>
==Formative years== Mukerjee was the son of a [[barrister]] in [[Baharampur]], [[West Bengal]], a city located some 185&nbsp;km north of [[Kolkata]]. He grew up in a household with a scholarly focus and a library devoted to [[history]], [[literature]], the [[law]] and [[Sanskrit]] texts. After attending Krishnanagar College, he gained an academic scholarship to [[Presidency College, Kolkata|Presidency College]], under the [[University of Calcutta]]. He earned his honours degrees in [[English language|English]] and [[History]].<ref>[http://www.ignou.ac.in/edusat/BDP/ESO13/pdf/ESOB1U5.pdf "5.3 Radhakamal Mukerjee (1889-1968), 5.3.1 Biographical Sketch", in ''History and Development of Sociology in India II.'' Central Digital Repository, Indira Gandhi National Open University] {{dead link|date=April 2015}}</ref>
==Literary works== Mukerjee opened the discourse of the [[Ashtavakra Gita]] into English with his [[Posthumous publication|posthumous]] work published in 1971.<ref>Radhakamal Mukerjee (1971). ''The song of the self supreme (Aṣṭāvakragītā): the classical text of Ātmādvaita by Aṣṭāvakra.'' Motilal Banarsidass Publ. {{ISBN|81-208-1367-7}}, {{ISBN|978-81-208-1367-0}}. Source: [https://books.google.com/books?id=hL-0qeeuVVIC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=&f=false] (accessed: Friday 19 March 2010)</ref>
==Early life== Mukherjees theory of society sought to explain the values of civilization.<ref>http://www.sociologyguide.com/indian-thinkers/radhakamal-mukherjee.php</ref> In sense, Radhakamal was a pioneer of transdisciplinary approach in science.<ref name="yourarticlelibrary.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.yourarticlelibrary.com/sociology/radhakamal-mukerjee-biography-and-contribution-to-sociology/35010/|title=Radhakamal Mukerjee : Biography and Contribution to Sociology|date=11 April 2014|publisher=}}</ref>
==Work== Radhakamal Mukerjee emphasized interdisciplinary disciplinary approach towards the understanding of life.<ref name="yourarticlelibrary.com"/> Mukerjee sought to break the barriers between physical sciences and sciences relating to persons aspects.<ref name="anlagepublishing.com">{{Cite web |url=http://www.anlagepublishing.com/teachers/Level_1/Mukerjee_Radhakamal.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=25 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110918204713/http://www.anlagepublishing.com/teachers/Level_1/Mukerjee_Radhakamal.html |archive-date=18 September 2011 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Mukerjee was a pioneer of Sociology in the 1900s.<ref name="anlagepublishing.com"/>
